# Next.js App Router — Server vs Client Components

In this project (`app/` directory), every component is a **React Server Component (RSC) by default**. Only add `'use client'` where truly necessary.

## When to use `'use client'`

- Uses React state (`useState`, `useReducer`)
- Uses effects (`useEffect`, `useLayoutEffect`)
- Uses browser APIs (`window`, `localStorage`, event handlers)
- Uses React Query hooks (`useQuery`, `useMutation`)

## Push `'use client'` to the leaves

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — wraps the whole page in a client boundary, losing RSC benefits
'use client';
export default function Page() {
  const { data } = useQuery({ queryKey: ['todos'], queryFn: fetchTodos });
  return <main><TodoList todos={data} /></main>;
}

// ✅ GOOD — page stays a Server Component; only the interactive part is client
// app/page.tsx (Server Component — no directive)
export default function Page() {
  return <main><TodoList /></main>; // TodoList.tsx has 'use client'
}

// components/TodoList.tsx
'use client';
export function TodoList() {
  const { data } = useQuery({ queryKey: ['todos'], queryFn: fetchTodos });
  ...
}
```

## `Providers.tsx` pattern

`QueryClientProvider` is already a client boundary in `Providers.tsx`. Components that only consume query data still need `'use client'` on themselves — being *under* a client provider does not make them client components automatically.

## Rules

- `app/layout.tsx` and `app/page.tsx` must remain Server Components unless there is a compelling reason.
- Do not fetch data in client components with `fetch` directly — use React Query hooks.
- Async Server Components can `await` data directly; no hooks needed.
- Keep `'use client'` as the **very first line** of the file (before imports).
